LEGS. Pairs 1 and 2 shortest, with very thin prefemur and femur, mesally with tarsal brushes; coxa 2 with gland opening; pairs 3 and 4 (
Fig. 5A
) very thick, with stout, shortly bifurcated bump dorso-parabasally on prefemur; 5–7 increasingly longer, tarsus of 7 (
Fig. 5B
) very long, ca 1.6 times as long as postfemur + tibia; coxa 10 (
Fig. 5C
) ventrally expanding into cylindrical process, expanding apically into somewhat curved, foam-like protrusion; coxa 11 (
Fig. 5D
) with two processes: a proximal, ventral one, similar to that on coxa 10, the other a distal, ventro-anterior, short and blunt, process; leg 24 ca 1.3 times as long as mid-body height, its tarsus ca 2 times as long as postfemur + tibia.
